            <h3 class="card-title">A Highly Searched Topic</h3>
            <p class="card-description">
              Tens of thousands of homeowners just like you search for answers about <a href="/restoration/mold-remediation/mold-testing" class="inline-link">mold testing</a> every month. This chart shows the massive search volume for just two key terms, highlighting how common this concern is.
            </p>
            <div class="chart-container">
              <canvas id="searchVolumeChart"></canvas>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Limitations Section -->
      <section id="limitations" class="guide-section">
        <div class="container">
          <div class="section-intro">
            <span class="badge badge-orange">Accuracy & Limitations</span>
            <h2 class="section-title">What DIY Kits Can (and Can't) Do</h2>
            <p class="section-description">
              DIY kits seem like a simple solution for diagnosis, but it's crucial to understand what their results *really* mean. Most common kits (like petri dishes) are simple "settling plates."
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="comparison-grid">
            <div class="comparison-card can-do">
              <h3 class="comparison-title">
                <span class="check-icon">✔</span> What Kits CAN Tell You
              </h3>
              <ul class="comparison-list">
                <li>
                  <span class="list-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>
                    <strong>If Mold Spores Are Present:</strong> A basic petri dish kit will likely grow *something*. Why? Because mold spores are almost always present in the air, both indoors and outdoors.
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="list-icon">✓</span>
                  <div>
                    <strong>A "Yes/No" for Spore Activity:</strong> Seeing growth confirms that spores in your air are viable. This is a very basic, non-specific confirmation.
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="comparison-card cannot-do">
              <h3 class="comparison-title">
                <span class="x-icon">✖</span> What Kits CAN'T Tell You
              </h3>
              <ul class="comparison-list">
                <li>
                  <span class="list-icon">!</span>
                  <div>
                    <strong>The Type of Mold:</strong> Identifying mold species (e.g., "<a href="/restoration/mold-remediation/black-mold-removal" class="inline-link">toxic black mold</a>") requires a microscope and a trained mycologist. A picture of a petri dish is not a diagnosis.
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="list-icon">!</span>
                  <div>
                    <strong>The Concentration (How Much):</strong> The kit can't tell you if the spore level is normal or dangerously elevated. A <a href="/restoration/mold-remediation/mold-inspection" class="inline-link">professional air test</a> compares indoor vs. outdoor spore counts for a real baseline.
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="list-icon">!</span>
                  <div>
                    <strong>The Source of the Problem:</strong> The test doesn't tell you *where* the mold is coming from (e.g., a <a href="/restoration/water-damage/leak-repair" class="inline-link">hidden leak in a wall</a>). This is the most critical piece of information you need.
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Error Section -->
      <section id="error" class="guide-section error-section">
        <div class="container">
          <div class="section-intro">
            <span class="badge badge-red">The Common Error Costing Thousands</span>
            <h2 class="section-title">The Pitfall of a Positive Test</h2>
            <p class="section-description">
              The biggest risk isn't the $50 kit. It's making a $5,000 decision based on incomplete data. A positive DIY test often leads to panic, but it's not an actionable diagnosis.
            </p>
          </div>

